                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d221">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.51/977.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Chargé d’Affaires</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Kineo, Me.</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-06-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 30, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>British minister in Peking has been instructed, if similar instructions are
                    received by his colleagues, to inform the Chinese Government that powers would
                    not approve of any loan by their nationals except on the general lines laid down
                    in conditions stipulated in the telegram sent by the groups on May 15, to which
                    the British Government had provisionally assented. The British Government does
                    not attach particular importance to the financial-agency scheme, as its only
                    object is to insure wise and effective control of expenditure, whether through
                    an agency or otherwise.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Mitchell Innes.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
